      <hedline>
        <hl1>Hebron Sovereignty</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>David Westrich letter disputes Thomas L Friedman's suggestion (August 11 Op-Ed column) that Israel grant Palestinians sovereignty over most of Old City of Jerusalem and share sovereignty over Temple Mount</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman (column, Aug. 11) proposes that Israel grant the Palestinians sovereignty over most of the Old City of Jerusalem and share sovereignty over the Temple Mount.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thomas L. Friedman (column, Aug. 11) proposes that Israel grant the Palestinians sovereignty over most of the Old City of Jerusalem and share sovereignty over the Temple Mount.</p>
        <p>Does Mr. Friedman also recognize the need for continued Israeli sovereignty over Hebron, which is at least as integral to Jewish history and faith as Jerusalem is to the Muslims? Hebron was King David's capital, is the burial place of Abraham, Isaac and Jacob, and is a close second to Jerusalem in holiness for Jews.</p>
        <p>DAVID WESTRICH  Teaneck, N.J., Aug. 13, 2000</p>
      </block>
